            </text>
            <standOff>
                <listAnnotation xml:lang="en" type="typednotes">
                    
                    	<note xml:id="n_transcrSource" type="transcrSource">
                    	    
<p>Original manuscript</p>
                    	</note>
                    
                    
                    	<note xml:id="n_dating" type="dating">
                    	    
<p>The fragment, which is part of an earlier version of <ref target="let627.xml">letter 627</ref>, was probably written on the same day as that letter, which dates from about Sunday, 17 June 1888.</p>
                    	</note>
                    
                    
                    
                    	<note xml:id="n_remarks" type="remarks">
                    	    
                                    
    <p>This sketch with a fragment of a letter was sent to John Russell, together with <ref target="let627.xml">letter 627</ref>. Appearing on the back of <hi rend="italics">Head of a girl</hi> (<rs type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#_175">F 1507a / JH 1466</rs>) is a fragment of text that was part of an earlier version of that letter (which explains why both the letter and this fragment mention the same things), in which Van Gogh writes: ‘I was writing to you and ... instead of continuing the letter I began to draw on the very paper the head of a dirty little girl ... I enclose the slip of scribbling.’ See also exhib. cat. New York 1984, pp. 105, 255, cat. no. 51; cat. New York 1992, p. 178.</p>
                                    
                                
                    	</note>
                    
                </listAnnotation>
                <listAnnotation xml:lang="en" type="ogtnotes">
                    
                </listAnnotation>
                <listAnnotation xml:lang="en" type="notes">
                    
                        <note n="1" xml:id="note-t-1">
                            
        
<p>This painting by <rs type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1222">Monet</rs> is <hi rend="italics"><rs type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#ill_1593">Under the pine trees at the end of the day</rs></hi>: <ref target="let615.xml#n-11">see letter 615, n. 11.</ref> Theo sold the work to Paul Aubry for 2800 francs on 29 June 1888. See Wildenstein 1996, cat. no. 1191 and exhib. cat. Amsterdam 1999, p. 215.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                            

                        
                    
